92, during a period of relative tolerance and economic prosperity. In newly-Muslim Oran, Jewish merchants found opportunities to ply their trades, dealing in both imports and exports. On the eve of France's long and brutal invasion of Algeria, Oran owed much of its commercial vitality to the success of these Jewish merchants. Under French occupation, the merchants of Oran maintained their commercial, political, and social clout. Yet by the 1840s, French policies began collapsing Oran's diverse Jewish inhabitants into a single social category, legally separating Jews from their Muslim neighbors and creating a racial hierarchy. Schreier argues that France's exclusionary policy of "emancipation," far more than older antipathies, planted the seeds of twentieth-century ruptures between Muslims and Jews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aJewish merchantszAlgeriazOranvBiography. 0aJewish merchantszAlgeriazOranxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszAlgeriazOranxHistoryy19th century. 4aAlgeria. 4aColonialism. 4aFrance. 4aGibraltar. 4aJews/Judaism. 4aMerchant(s). 4aMorocco. 4aMuslims. 4aNorth Africa. 4aOran. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503602168zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503602168423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503602168.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles